03960nam a22006375i 9780857455468DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574554687 a10.1515/97808574554682doi  a(DE-B1597)637243  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN1998.3 .H36 W44 2011 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43023/30922221 aWheatley, Catherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMichael Haneke's Cinema :bThe Ethic of the Image /cCatherine Wheatley. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (234 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm Europa ;v700tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tDECLARATION -- tA NOTE ON THE TITLES -- tACKNOWLEDGEMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tChapter 1 THE LAST MORALIST? -- tChapter 2 NEGOTIATING MODERNISM Der Siebente Kontinent, Benny’s Video, 71 Fragmente einer Chronologie des Zufalls -- tChapter 3 THE ETHICS OF AGGRESSION: Funny Games -- tChapter 4 EMOTIONAL ENGAGEMENT AND NARRATIVITY Code inconnu, La Pianiste, Le Temps du loup -- tChapter 5 SHAME AND GUILT Caché -- tCONCLUSION -- tAppendix I MICHAEL HANEKE FILMOGRAPHY -- tAppendix II MICHAEL HANEKE AT THE BOX OFFICE -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExisting critical traditions fail to fully account for the impact of Austrian director, and 2009 Cannes Palm d'Or winner, Michael Haneke’s films, situated as they are between intellectual projects and popular entertainments. In this first English-language introduction to, and critical analysis of, his work, each of Haneke’s eight feature films are considered in detail. Particular attention is given to what the author terms Michael Haneke’s ‘ethical cinema’ and the unique impact of these films upon their audiences. Drawing on the moral philosophy of Immanuel Kant and Stanley Cavell, Catherine Wheatley, introduces a new way of marrying film and moral philosophy, which explicitly examines the ethics of the film viewing experience. Haneke’s films offer the viewer great freedom whilst simultaneously imposing a considerable burden of responsibility. How Haneke achieves this break with more conventional spectatorship models, and what its far-reaching implications are for film theory in general, constitute the principal subject of this book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745546840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857455468423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857455468/original  a978-3-11-099828-3  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK